{"attributes":{"backlinks":[],"path":"/Users/lorenz/.julia/packages/PolyChaos/THVqe/docs/src/orthogonal_polynomials_canonical.md","title":"[Univariate Monic Orthogonal Polynomials]( UnivariateMonicOrthogonalPolynomials)"},"tag":"document","children":[{"attributes":{},"tag":"md","children":[{"attributes":{},"tag":"h1","children":["[Univariate Monic Orthogonal Polynomials](",{"attributes":{},"tag":"citation","children":[{"mimes":{"text/plain":"Any[]"},"type":"leaf"},{"mimes":{"text/plain":"Dict{Symbol, String}()"},"type":"leaf"}],"type":"node"}," UnivariateMonicOrthogonalPolynomials)"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"p","children":["Univariate monic orthogonal polynomials make up the core building block of the package. These are real polynomials ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["\\{ \\pi_k \\}_{k \\geq 0}"],"type":"node"},", which are univariate ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["\\pi_k: \\mathbb{R} \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}"],"type":"node"}," and orthogonal relative to a nonnegative weight function ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["w: \\mathbb{R} \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}_{\\geq 0}"],"type":"node"},", and which have a leading coefficient equal to one:"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"mathblock","children":["\\begin{aligned}\n\\pi_k(t) &= t^k + a_{k-1} t^{k-1} + \\dots + a_1 t + a_0 \\quad \\forall k = 0, 1, \\dots \\\\\n\\langle \\pi_k, \\pi_l \\rangle &= \\int_{\\mathbb{R}} \\pi_k(t) \\pi_l(t) w(t) \\mathrm{d}t =\n\\begin{cases}\n0 & k \\neq l, \\text{ and }k,l \\geq 0 \\\\\n\\| \\pi_k \\|^2 > 0 & k = l \\geq 0\n\\end{cases}\n\\end{aligned}"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"p","children":["These univariate monic orthogonal polynomials satisfy the paramount three-term recurrence relation"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"mathblock","children":["\\begin{aligned}\n\\pi_{k+1}(t) &= (t - \\alpha_k) \\pi_k(t) - \\beta_k \\pi_{k-1}(t), \\quad k= 0, 1, \\dots, \\\\\n\\pi_o(t) &= 1, \\\\\n\\pi_{-1}(t) &= 0.\n\\end{aligned}"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"p","children":["Hence, every system of ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["n"],"type":"node"}," univariate monic orthogonal polynomials ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["\\{ \\pi_k \\}_{k=0}^n"],"type":"node"}," is isomorphic to its recurrence coefficients ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["\\{ \\alpha_k, \\beta_k \\}_{k=0}^n"],"type":"node"},"."],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"h2","children":["Canonical Orthogonal Polynomials"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"p","children":["The so-called ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["classical"],"type":"node"}," or ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["canonical"],"type":"node"}," orthogonal polynomials are polynomials named after famous mathematicians who each discovered a special family of orthogonal polynomials, for example ",{"attributes":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermite_polynomials","title":""},"tag":"a","children":["Hermite polynomials"],"type":"node"}," or ",{"attributes":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobi_polynomials","title":""},"tag":"a","children":["Jacobi polynomials"],"type":"node"},". For ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["classical"],"type":"node"}," orthogonal polynomials there exist closed-form expressions of---among others---the recurrence coefficients. Also quadrature rules for ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["classical"],"type":"node"}," orthogonal polynomials are well-studied (with dedicated packages such as ",{"attributes":{"href":"https://github.com/ajt60gaibb/FastGaussQuadrature.jl","title":""},"tag":"a","children":["FastGaussQuadrature.jl"],"type":"node"},". However, more often than not these ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["classical"],"type":"node"}," orthogonal polynomials are neither monic nor orthogonal, hence not normalized in any sense. For example, there is a distinction between the ",{"attributes":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermite_polynomials#Definition","title":""},"tag":"a","children":[{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["probabilists'"],"type":"node"}," Hermite polynomials"],"type":"node"}," and the ",{"attributes":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermite_polynomials#Definition","title":""},"tag":"a","children":[{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["physicists'"],"type":"node"}," Hermite polynomials"],"type":"node"},". The difference is in the weight function ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["w(t)"],"type":"node"}," relative to which the polynomials are orthogonal:"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"mathblock","children":["\\begin{aligned}\n&\\text{Probabilists':} &&&w(t) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2 \\pi}} \\, \\exp \\left( - \\frac{t^2}{2} \\right) \\\\\n&\\text{Physicists':} &&&w(t) =  \\exp \\left( - t^2 \\right).\n\\end{aligned}"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"p","children":["To streamline the computations, all ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["classical"],"type":"node"}," orthogonal polynomials are converted to ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"strong","children":["monic"],"type":"node"}," orthogonal polynomials (for which, of course, the closed-form expressions persist). Currently, the following weight functions (hence ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["classical"],"type":"node"}," orthogonal polynomials) are supported:"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{"align":["left","left","left","left","left"]},"tag":"table","children":[{"attributes":{},"tag":"tr","children":[{"attributes":{},"tag":"th","children":["Name"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"th","children":["Weight ",{"attributes":{},"tag":"math","children":["w(t)"],"type":"node"}],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"th","children":["Parameters"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"th","children":["Support"],"type":"node"},{"attributes":{},"tag":"th","children":["",{"attributes":{},"tag":"em","children":["Classical"],"type":"node"}," polynomial"],"type":"node"}],"type":"node